1
00:01:36,596 --> 00:01:37,961
<i>Where is our navy?</i>

2
00:01:38,031 --> 00:01:39,464
<i>Three months have passed</i>

3
00:01:39,532 --> 00:01:41,966
<i>since the tragedy</i>
<i>at Pearl Harbor...</i>

4
00:01:42,035 --> 00:01:45,471
<i>1 2 die as Jap submarines</i>
<i>strike near San Francisco.</i>

5
00:01:45,538 --> 00:01:50,669
<i>Committee demands probe</i>
<i>of navy failure to fight.</i>

6
00:01:50,743 --> 00:01:55,874
<i>Where is our navy?</i>
<i>Why doesn't it fight?</i>

7
00:01:55,949 --> 00:01:57,883
We cannot
answer that question.

8
00:01:57,951 --> 00:02:01,318
We must force ourselves
not to listen to it.

9
00:02:01,387 --> 00:02:04,322
We do not intend
to tell theJapanese

10
00:02:04,390 --> 00:02:07,826
how badly our navy
was damaged at Pearl Harbor.

11
00:02:07,894 --> 00:02:09,327
Since December the 7 th,

12
00:02:09,395 --> 00:02:12,660
our prewar strategy
is useless.

13
00:02:12,732 --> 00:02:14,256
The defense
of the Aleutians

14
00:02:14,334 --> 00:02:16,768
and our Pacific Coast
with the Hawaiis

15
00:02:16,836 --> 00:02:18,929
at the apex
of the Triangle

16
00:02:19,005 --> 00:02:20,165
is almost impossible

17
00:02:20,240 --> 00:02:22,674
with what remains
of our navy.

18
00:02:22,742 --> 00:02:25,677
But we are not considering
a defensive campaign.

19
00:02:25,745 --> 00:02:27,178
You all realize

20
00:02:27,247 --> 00:02:29,681
I'm indulging in
no false heroics

21
00:02:29,749 --> 00:02:31,182
when I say

22
00:02:31,251 --> 00:02:33,685
our only hope
of evading destruction

23
00:02:33,753 --> 00:02:35,687
is to destroy
the enemy.

24
00:02:35,755 --> 00:02:37,188
TheJapanese have won

25
00:02:37,257 --> 00:02:40,192
a quick and staggering
succession of victories.

26
00:02:40,260 --> 00:02:43,195
They're aiming now
at the final knockout--

27
00:02:43,263 --> 00:02:45,197
the capture
of Pearl Harbor.

28
00:02:45,265 --> 00:02:46,698
To accomplish this,

29
00:02:46,766 --> 00:02:50,031
they must first
take Midway.

30
00:02:50,103 --> 00:02:51,536
If they are permitted

31
00:02:51,604 --> 00:02:54,539
to choose the time
and conditions of attack,

32
00:02:54,607 --> 00:02:57,041
we haven't
much of a chance,

33
00:02:57,110 --> 00:03:00,477
but if we can trick them
into meeting us

34
00:03:00,547 --> 00:03:02,981
when they think
we are weak,

35
00:03:03,049 --> 00:03:04,983
we then have a chance

36
00:03:05,051 --> 00:03:07,986
of cutting their navy
down to our size

37
00:03:08,054 --> 00:03:11,490
and proceeding with the rest
of the Pacific strategy.

38
00:03:11,558 --> 00:03:12,991
We have learned

39
00:03:13,059 --> 00:03:15,994
there are heavy concentrations
of enemy carriers

40
00:03:16,062 --> 00:03:19,498
and other fleet units
in the Marshall Islands

41
00:03:19,566 --> 00:03:21,727
and a numerous
transport force

42
00:03:21,801 --> 00:03:22,995
making up at Truk.

43
00:03:23,069 --> 00:03:26,197
So our strategy is this.

44
00:03:36,182 --> 00:03:39,345
We shall concentrate
our strength near Midway

45
00:03:39,419 --> 00:03:42,354
in our effort
to spring a trap.

46
00:03:42,422 --> 00:03:45,255
One of our carriers
is already at sea

47
00:03:45,325 --> 00:03:47,759
waiting to carry out
the initial phases

48
00:03:47,827 --> 00:03:48,919
of this strategy.

49
00:03:48,995 --> 00:03:49,927
On April the 28th,

50
00:03:49,996 --> 00:03:51,759
this carrier
and its escort

51
00:03:51,831 --> 00:03:54,265
will be off
the Marshall Islands,

52
00:03:54,334 --> 00:03:56,268
close enough
to be detected.

53
00:03:56,336 --> 00:03:57,325
On May the 3rd,

54
00:03:57,403 --> 00:04:00,201
it is to be seen
near the Gilbert Islands

55
00:04:00,273 --> 00:04:01,205
by theJapanese.

56
00:04:01,274 --> 00:04:02,241
On May the 8th,

57
00:04:02,308 --> 00:04:04,708
it will be detected
near Ocean Island,

58
00:04:04,777 --> 00:04:07,211
as if heading
for theJap fleet at Truk,

59
00:04:07,280 --> 00:04:09,214
but it will not attack.

60
00:04:09,282 --> 00:04:10,715
It will turn south,

61
00:04:10,783 --> 00:04:13,752
be seen on May the 1 5th
at Guadalcanal.

62
00:04:21,127 --> 00:04:25,063
Every time one of our pilots
encounters a Jap plane,

63
00:04:25,131 --> 00:04:27,565
he will return
to the carrier,

64
00:04:27,634 --> 00:04:30,569
as if he did
not stomach a fight.

65
00:04:30,637 --> 00:04:34,073
By sending this one carrier
on such a mission,

66
00:04:34,140 --> 00:04:36,574
we hope
to convince the enemy

67
00:04:36,643 --> 00:04:38,577
that our fleet
is scattered,

68
00:04:38,645 --> 00:04:42,911
our fighting morale...
shattered.

69
00:04:42,982 --> 00:04:46,418
Actually, we shall be
waiting for them in force

70
00:04:46,486 --> 00:04:47,418
near Midway.

71
00:04:47,487 --> 00:04:49,921
If they fall
for this bait

72
00:04:49,989 --> 00:04:51,422
and attempt an invasion,

73
00:04:51,491 --> 00:04:55,427
we shall then be able
to answer the question--

74
00:04:55,495 --> 00:04:57,793
''Where is our navy?

75
00:04:57,864 --> 00:04:59,456
Why doesn't it fight?''

76
00:05:24,223 --> 00:05:25,656
Pilot to crew.

77
00:05:26,759 --> 00:05:28,192
There's mama.

78
00:05:35,168 --> 00:05:36,726
I see her, Commander.

79
00:05:47,046 --> 00:05:48,172
Pilot to crew.

80
00:05:49,282 --> 00:05:50,874
If you need
a toothpick,

81
00:05:50,950 --> 00:05:54,044
I know where
you can find one.

82
00:05:55,555 --> 00:05:58,524
We'd only need
half that space, Mr. Scott.

83
00:05:58,591 --> 00:06:00,684
Just lower your wheels
and drop your hook,

84
00:06:00,760 --> 00:06:02,694
like putting
a baby to bed.

85
00:06:31,157 --> 00:06:33,387
<i>Set condition one</i>
<i>in the air department.</i>

86
00:06:33,459 --> 00:06:35,689
<i>Stand by</i>
<i>to land planes.</i>

87
00:06:35,762 --> 00:06:37,855
<i>Stand by</i>
<i>to land planes.</i>

88
00:07:08,861 --> 00:07:11,796
Torpedo planes sighted
broad on the port quarter.

89
00:07:11,864 --> 00:07:13,297
Altitude 2-5-0-0.

90
00:07:13,366 --> 00:07:14,799
Range 8,000 yards.

91
00:07:14,867 --> 00:07:16,892
Stand by
for practice run.

92
00:07:19,038 --> 00:07:22,735
If those were only meatballs
instead ofTBFs.

93
00:07:41,294 --> 00:07:42,454
O.K. Hook.

94
00:08:15,761 --> 00:08:17,319
Stand clear.

95
00:08:51,297 --> 00:08:54,391
I'm O'Donnell, commanding Bomber Six.
Welcome aboard.

96
00:08:54,467 --> 00:08:55,764
Molton, commanding
Torpedo Five.

97
00:08:55,835 --> 00:08:57,769
What's the scuttlebutt?
What gives?

98
00:08:57,837 --> 00:09:01,204
I thought we'd find out
when we got aboard.

99
00:09:01,274 --> 00:09:02,673
Not from us.

100
00:09:02,742 --> 00:09:05,176
I thought with
you guys aboard,

101
00:09:05,244 --> 00:09:06,677
we'd have some action.

102
00:09:06,746 --> 00:09:07,678
Name's Shubert.

103
00:09:07,747 --> 00:09:09,681
I'm Manning.
We're on a cook's tour.

104
00:09:09,749 --> 00:09:11,774
Your guess is
as good as mine.

105
00:09:11,851 --> 00:09:13,011
See you around.

106
00:09:29,602 --> 00:09:31,035
Sir.

107
00:09:31,103 --> 00:09:32,536
Lieutenant Commander
Edward Molton

108
00:09:32,605 --> 00:09:34,539
reporting for
Torpedo Squadron Five.

109
00:09:34,607 --> 00:09:36,541
Glad to have you aboard.

110
00:09:36,609 --> 00:09:39,043
Molton, Commander Harper,
our air officer.

111
00:09:39,111 --> 00:09:40,043
How do you do?

112
00:09:40,112 --> 00:09:41,044
Good to see you.

113
00:09:41,113 --> 00:09:43,104
I've a message for you.

114
00:09:59,432 --> 00:10:00,797
Hey, what's eating Oscar?

115
00:10:00,866 --> 00:10:02,458
Sure making
a long approach.

116
00:10:02,535 --> 00:10:04,503
He's building up
an entrance.

117
00:10:34,867 --> 00:10:37,461
Just feel your way
in, sir. Lightly.

118
00:10:37,536 --> 00:10:38,696
And politely.

119
00:11:08,434 --> 00:11:10,698
Do we have
to shoot him down?

120
00:11:19,345 --> 00:11:22,576
What does he want,
a spotlight?

121
00:11:57,950 --> 00:12:00,077
He's coming in too fast.

122
00:12:07,126 --> 00:12:09,185
Can't he see
that wave-off?

123
00:12:09,261 --> 00:12:10,922
[Siren Sounds]

124
00:12:33,886 --> 00:12:36,821
Assemble your squadron
in the ready room.

125
00:12:36,889 --> 00:12:38,322
Aye, aye, sir.

126
00:12:43,729 --> 00:12:46,664
Boy, I thought
for a while there...

127
00:12:46,732 --> 00:12:48,597
until 1 900...

128
00:12:48,667 --> 00:12:50,828
I thought I'd have
to turn back.

129
00:12:50,903 --> 00:12:52,564
Maybe you should have.

130
00:12:52,638 --> 00:12:54,572
Didn't you see
the wave-off?

131
00:12:54,640 --> 00:12:55,698
Yes, sir.

132
00:12:55,775 --> 00:12:58,505
Did you think the flagman
was waving bye-bye?

133
00:12:58,577 --> 00:13:01,444
To tell you the truth,
I couldn't think.

134
00:13:01,514 --> 00:13:04,449
I had my hands
too full of airplane

135
00:13:04,517 --> 00:13:06,109
at the time.

136
00:13:06,185 --> 00:13:07,948
Oh.

137
00:13:08,020 --> 00:13:09,180
But--

138
00:13:10,556 --> 00:13:13,992
Oh, men, this is our air officer
Commander Harper.

139
00:13:15,127 --> 00:13:16,992
Commander Harper,
this is Mr. Brainard,

140
00:13:17,263 --> 00:13:18,707
Mr. Chisholm.

141
00:13:18,841 --> 00:13:19,364
Mr. Markham.

142
00:13:19,441 --> 00:13:20,373
How do you do?

143
00:13:20,442 --> 00:13:21,374
Mr.Jacobson.

144
00:13:21,443 --> 00:13:22,375
How do you do?

145
00:13:22,444 --> 00:13:23,376
Mr. White.

146
00:13:23,445 --> 00:13:24,377
Sir.

147
00:13:24,446 --> 00:13:25,378
Mr. Holloway.

148
00:13:25,447 --> 00:13:26,379
Mr. Scott.

149
00:13:26,448 --> 00:13:27,972
How do you do?

150
00:13:34,957 --> 00:13:36,891
I'm glad to know you

151
00:13:36,959 --> 00:13:38,153
and welcome you aboard.

152
00:13:38,227 --> 00:13:40,388
- Thank you.
- Thank you, sir.

153
00:13:40,462 --> 00:13:42,396
You've been assigned
to quarters

154
00:13:42,464 --> 00:13:45,399
which I hope you find
to your liking.

155
00:13:45,467 --> 00:13:47,731
We have some pretty
good men on board.

156
00:13:47,803 --> 00:13:50,738
I've been very proud of
all of our squadrons--

157
00:13:50,806 --> 00:13:52,239
torpedoes,
bombers, and fighters.

158
00:13:52,307 --> 00:13:55,003
I hope
you equal their record.

159
00:13:56,979 --> 00:13:58,913
Read that, please,
Mr. Molton.

160
00:14:00,449 --> 00:14:01,609
Aloud.

161
00:14:03,419 --> 00:14:05,853
'' Memorandum for commander,
Air Group Five.

162
00:14:05,921 --> 00:14:07,786
Subject--
Report of casualty

163
00:14:07,856 --> 00:14:09,289
which occurred
during maneuvers,

164
00:14:09,358 --> 00:14:11,292
September 1 9, 1 941 .

165
00:14:11,360 --> 00:14:13,294
Roy K. Spangler,
number 43 281 1 2,

166
00:14:13,362 --> 00:14:14,795
aviation machinist's mate,

167
00:14:14,863 --> 00:14:17,855
first class,
United States Navy,

168
00:14:17,933 --> 00:14:20,367
died at 1 600
while under anesthesia

169
00:14:20,436 --> 00:14:25,032
for surgery following
accident on flight deck.

170
00:14:25,107 --> 00:14:26,540
Spangler's next of kin,

171
00:14:26,608 --> 00:14:29,042
his mother
Mrs. Edward R. Spangler,

172
00:14:29,111 --> 00:14:30,635
361 7 Lee Avenue,

173
00:14:30,713 --> 00:14:32,044
Minneapolis, Minnesota.

174
00:14:32,114 --> 00:14:35,379
Signed J.B. Golden, commander,
senior medical officer.''

175
00:14:36,452 --> 00:14:39,387
A hot pilot
ignored a wave-off.

176
00:14:39,455 --> 00:14:40,945
Spangler couldn't
get out of the way.

177
00:14:41,023 --> 00:14:44,220
The prop cut him
nearly in half.

178
00:14:46,462 --> 00:14:48,327
I'm sorry, sir.

179
00:14:48,397 --> 00:14:50,331
So was the other pilot.

180
00:14:50,399 --> 00:14:51,866
So was
Spangler's mother.

181
00:14:51,934 --> 00:14:54,300
I'd like
to explain, sir--

182
00:14:54,369 --> 00:14:55,802
I don't
like explanations.

183
00:15:10,953 --> 00:15:12,477
Secure.

184
00:15:21,830 --> 00:15:22,854
Sorry, sir.

185
00:15:22,931 --> 00:15:25,866
The way you and the
others had to take it

186
00:15:25,934 --> 00:15:26,923
on account of me.

187
00:15:27,002 --> 00:15:29,527
Just don't ignore
any more wave-offs.

188
00:15:29,605 --> 00:15:31,095
Aye, aye, sir.

189
00:15:35,644 --> 00:15:36,576
Mr. Scott.

190
00:15:36,645 --> 00:15:38,237
Here's some
mail for you.

191
00:15:39,314 --> 00:15:40,406
Oh, thanks.

192
00:15:40,482 --> 00:15:45,010
I see the movie fans
haven't forgotten you, sir.

193
00:15:49,424 --> 00:15:51,153
Cunningham?

194
00:15:51,226 --> 00:15:52,250
Yes, sir.

195
00:15:52,327 --> 00:15:54,386
I've received this letter
from the admiral.

196
00:15:54,463 --> 00:15:56,897
I thought you'd
like to read it.

197
00:16:06,909 --> 00:16:08,103
Congratulations.

198
00:16:09,845 --> 00:16:10,777
Gentlemen!

199
00:16:10,846 --> 00:16:11,778
Gentlemen!

200
00:16:11,847 --> 00:16:14,577
I give you
Cookie Cunningham!

201
00:16:14,650 --> 00:16:17,448
The man who studied
Japanese mathematics

202
00:16:17,519 --> 00:16:20,454
and found you always
get the right answer

203
00:16:20,522 --> 00:16:22,285
by subtracting zero.

204
00:16:26,295 --> 00:16:29,230
Who says we don't know
where we're going?

205
00:16:29,298 --> 00:16:32,233
I tell you what
I'm going to do.

206
00:16:32,301 --> 00:16:34,565
I'll fly my TBF
clear to Tokyo.

207
00:16:34,636 --> 00:16:37,070
I'll drag that
little monkey to 1 5,000

208
00:16:37,139 --> 00:16:39,573
and drop him
like a bomb,

209
00:16:39,641 --> 00:16:40,665
right smack on Fujiyama.

210
00:16:40,742 --> 00:16:43,176
I can't stand the
canned vegetables

211
00:16:43,245 --> 00:16:44,678
you get
on shipboard.

212
00:16:44,746 --> 00:16:46,179
But our squadron's
different.

213
00:16:46,248 --> 00:16:47,510
We'll have
fresh vegetables.

214
00:16:47,583 --> 00:16:48,515
How come?

215
00:16:48,584 --> 00:16:49,608
How?

216
00:16:50,853 --> 00:16:53,788
You going to plow up
the flight deck?

217
00:16:53,856 --> 00:16:54,914
No, I'm not kidding.

218
00:16:54,990 --> 00:16:56,924
We'll have
some fresh celery,

219
00:16:56,992 --> 00:16:58,789
real juicy tomatoes,
green onions--

220
00:16:58,861 --> 00:17:01,728
What are you going
to use for dirt?

221
00:17:01,797 --> 00:17:03,230
Water and chemicals.

222
00:17:03,298 --> 00:17:04,356
That's the agriculture
of the future.

223
00:17:04,433 --> 00:17:07,095
Ya-hoo!

224
00:17:07,169 --> 00:17:08,101
Hey, fellows!

225
00:17:08,170 --> 00:17:09,102
Look!

226
00:17:09,171 --> 00:17:12,038
Get a load of this!

227
00:17:12,107 --> 00:17:13,631
Wait a minute!

228
00:17:13,709 --> 00:17:14,641
Hey, wait!

229
00:17:14,710 --> 00:17:16,200
Now don't do that.

230
00:17:16,278 --> 00:17:17,643
You did it!

231
00:17:17,713 --> 00:17:19,647
It shows it right there.

232
00:17:19,715 --> 00:17:21,148
You kissed Betty Grable.

233
00:17:21,216 --> 00:17:24,208
If I didn't see it,
I wouldn't believe it.

234
00:17:24,286 --> 00:17:25,719
Did you
ever kiss Garbo?

235
00:17:25,787 --> 00:17:26,719
I've never seen her.

236
00:17:26,788 --> 00:17:29,222
When you're in a picture

237
00:17:29,291 --> 00:17:32,055
and you have
to kiss Betty Grable--

238
00:17:32,127 --> 00:17:34,061
Listen to me--
<i>have to</i>--

239
00:17:34,129 --> 00:17:37,064
When you kiss her,
what's it feel like?

240
00:17:37,132 --> 00:17:38,565
Ah, let it lay.

241
00:17:38,634 --> 00:17:39,726
I'm serious
about this, Oscar.

242
00:17:39,801 --> 00:17:40,825
I really mean it.

243
00:17:40,903 --> 00:17:43,838
I mean, do you feel
anything at all,

244
00:17:43,906 --> 00:17:47,637
or is it all just
part of the day's work?

245
00:17:47,709 --> 00:17:48,801
Does she breathe deep?

246
00:17:48,877 --> 00:17:51,141
Does she kiss you
or you her?

247
00:17:51,213 --> 00:17:52,145
Does she kiss back?

248
00:17:52,214 --> 00:17:54,239
What I want to know is,

249
00:17:54,316 --> 00:17:56,750
how does it make
you feel?

250
00:17:56,818 --> 00:18:00,754
The rest of us can only dream
about those girls,

251
00:18:00,822 --> 00:18:03,188
but you've
actually kissed them.

252
00:18:03,258 --> 00:18:04,691
What's it like?

253
00:18:04,760 --> 00:18:06,694
Well, it's, uh...

254
00:18:06,762 --> 00:18:09,822
it's like nothing
else in this world.

255
00:18:09,898 --> 00:18:11,661
- Ahh.
- Ahh.

256
00:18:11,733 --> 00:18:14,167
I'll never forget
that first girl

257
00:18:14,236 --> 00:18:15,931
I kissed in a picture.

258
00:18:16,004 --> 00:18:17,028
Who was it?

259
00:18:17,105 --> 00:18:18,037
Yeah. Who?

260
00:18:18,106 --> 00:18:20,199
You think
I'd kiss and tell?

261
00:18:20,275 --> 00:18:21,708
In a wardroom?

262
00:18:21,777 --> 00:18:23,210
Come on, Oscar.

263
00:18:23,278 --> 00:18:25,143
Well, it's, um...

264
00:18:26,315 --> 00:18:29,216
The night before
the scene was to be shot,

265
00:18:29,284 --> 00:18:30,717
I didn't sleep.

266
00:18:30,786 --> 00:18:32,720
I lay awake all night,

267
00:18:32,788 --> 00:18:34,779
just daydreaming
about that kiss.

268
00:18:34,856 --> 00:18:36,585
How do you
daydream at night?

269
00:18:36,658 --> 00:18:37,590
Quiet.

270
00:18:37,659 --> 00:18:39,820
Well, how do you?

271
00:18:39,895 --> 00:18:41,328
The next morning

272
00:18:41,396 --> 00:18:43,296
I got to the studio
an hour earlier,

273
00:18:43,365 --> 00:18:44,798
got into my wardrobe,

274
00:18:44,866 --> 00:18:46,561
dashed over to the set.

275
00:18:46,635 --> 00:18:49,570
I waited all day
for that one moment

276
00:18:49,638 --> 00:18:52,072
when I'd get
to kiss her.

277
00:18:52,140 --> 00:18:55,576
Finally, it was time
for the scene to be shot.

278
00:18:55,644 --> 00:18:57,236
We took our places.

279
00:18:57,312 --> 00:19:00,406
She was wearing the most beautiful
black negligee.

280
00:19:00,482 --> 00:19:01,949
Lovely...

281
00:19:02,017 --> 00:19:03,882
revealing.

282
00:19:03,952 --> 00:19:06,512
Her hair was swept back
from her forehead.

283
00:19:06,588 --> 00:19:08,522
Her eyes
were partly closed.

284
00:19:08,590 --> 00:19:11,024
I took her
into my arms...

285
00:19:11,093 --> 00:19:13,823
Go on.
Kiss her, you dope!

286
00:19:13,895 --> 00:19:15,021
The hairdresser yelled,

287
00:19:15,097 --> 00:19:17,190
''You're mussing up
her hairdo.''

288
00:19:17,265 --> 00:19:20,701
The director screamed, '' Move your arm.
You're tilting her collar.''

289
00:19:20,769 --> 00:19:23,203
The cameraman said,
''I can't see her nose.''

290
00:19:23,271 --> 00:19:26,297
So I kissed her off-center
and smacked the air.

291
00:19:26,375 --> 00:19:28,536
If you want
to kiss a girl right,

292
00:19:28,610 --> 00:19:30,669
you got
to join the navy.

293
00:19:30,746 --> 00:19:33,681
Hey! You can't
get away with that!

294
00:19:35,450 --> 00:19:36,883
Hey! Hey! Gather 'round.

295
00:19:36,952 --> 00:19:39,386
I want
to tell you something.

296
00:19:39,454 --> 00:19:41,319
Your worries are over.

297
00:19:41,390 --> 00:19:44,553
Listen to the voice
of Superman.

298
00:19:46,194 --> 00:19:49,129
<i>I'll tell you what</i>
<i>I'm going to do.</i>

299
00:19:49,197 --> 00:19:52,132
<i>I'll fly my TBF</i>
<i>clear to Tokyo.</i>

300
00:19:52,200 --> 00:19:54,634
<i>Throw a rope</i>
<i>around Tojo's neck,</i>

301
00:19:54,703 --> 00:19:57,638
<i>like I roped coyotes</i>
<i>back in Texas.</i>

302
00:19:57,706 --> 00:20:00,641
<i>I'll drag that</i>
<i>monkey to 1 5,000 feet</i>

303
00:20:00,709 --> 00:20:02,734
<i>and drop him</i>
<i>like a bomb...</i>

304
00:20:02,811 --> 00:20:03,869
Very funny.

305
00:20:03,945 --> 00:20:07,244
I wouldn't want
to bore you guys

306
00:20:07,315 --> 00:20:09,749
with what I'm
really going to do.

307
00:20:09,818 --> 00:20:12,252
It sure takes
a load off our minds.

308
00:20:12,320 --> 00:20:14,584
That guy there
might possibly give you

309
00:20:14,656 --> 00:20:15,782
a few pointers.

310
00:20:15,857 --> 00:20:18,223
He's only shot down
three Zeros.

311
00:20:19,561 --> 00:20:22,496
I'm just a bag of wind
from Texas.

312
00:20:22,564 --> 00:20:23,997
I must sound funny

313
00:20:24,066 --> 00:20:26,933
to a guy who's done
the things you've done.

314
00:20:27,002 --> 00:20:28,094
How do you feel

315
00:20:28,170 --> 00:20:30,604
when those meatballs
come at you?

316
00:20:30,672 --> 00:20:32,105
I didn't see them

317
00:20:32,174 --> 00:20:33,266
until they were
pretty close.

318
00:20:33,341 --> 00:20:34,706
Did they attack
from above?

319
00:20:34,776 --> 00:20:35,708
From below.

320
00:20:35,777 --> 00:20:37,039
They missed
with their first pass.

321
00:20:37,112 --> 00:20:39,774
They say they can attack,
pull out,

322
00:20:39,848 --> 00:20:42,282
and dive again
before you see them.

323
00:20:42,350 --> 00:20:43,749
Slow but with
maneuverability?

324
00:20:43,819 --> 00:20:45,252
I don't know, really--

325
00:20:45,320 --> 00:20:48,255
They machine-gun you
on the way down?

326
00:20:48,323 --> 00:20:49,756
I'm writing my memoirs

327
00:20:49,825 --> 00:20:51,759
for <i>the Saturday Evening Post.</i>

328
00:20:51,827 --> 00:20:53,727
You can read them
after the war.

329
00:20:53,795 --> 00:20:55,729
All right.
Break it up.

330
00:20:55,797 --> 00:20:57,230
Let's cut a record.

331
00:20:57,299 --> 00:20:59,733
Hey, you want me
to make another one?

332
00:21:11,313 --> 00:21:14,248
I could knock that moon
out of the sky.

333
00:21:14,316 --> 00:21:15,749
Leave it alone.

334
00:21:15,817 --> 00:21:18,377
I'll need that moon
when I get home.

335
00:21:34,870 --> 00:21:36,428
Right on the beam, kid.

336
00:21:58,360 --> 00:21:59,793
What's your name?

337
00:21:59,861 --> 00:22:00,919
Benjamin K. O'Neal,
sir.

338
00:22:00,996 --> 00:22:02,361
Aviation radioman,
first class.

339
00:22:02,430 --> 00:22:04,625
Did you come in
with Torpedo Five?

340
00:22:04,699 --> 00:22:05,893
That's right, sir.

341
00:22:05,967 --> 00:22:07,730
Haven't you served
under me before?

342
00:22:07,802 --> 00:22:10,737
I was in and out
of Pensacola, sir.

343
00:22:10,805 --> 00:22:12,739
I thought I'd
seen you before.

344
00:22:12,807 --> 00:22:14,240
As you were.

345
00:22:15,744 --> 00:22:17,905
Bring back

346
00:22:17,979 --> 00:22:21,039
Bring back
my Bonny to me

347
00:22:21,116 --> 00:22:22,606
To me...

348
00:22:26,021 --> 00:22:27,454
What's wrong, Benny?

349
00:22:27,522 --> 00:22:30,252
I've been ducking him
since I came on board.

350
00:22:30,325 --> 00:22:33,260
If he figures how long
ago he saw me,

351
00:22:33,328 --> 00:22:34,761
he'll ground me sure.

352
00:22:34,829 --> 00:22:35,761
How come?

353
00:22:35,830 --> 00:22:37,263
Too old
for air combat duty.

354
00:22:37,332 --> 00:22:38,765
Are you kidding?

355
00:22:38,833 --> 00:22:39,857
There's no law--

356
00:22:39,935 --> 00:22:41,869
That man's
the whole navy

357
00:22:41,937 --> 00:22:43,768
in one pair of pants.

358
00:22:43,838 --> 00:22:46,773
Do you know what
kind of guy he is?

359
00:22:46,841 --> 00:22:50,777
He's the only officer whose men
wouldn't give him a nickname.

360
00:22:50,845 --> 00:22:52,472
What's the matter?

361
00:22:52,547 --> 00:22:54,777
What if he
finds out about me?

362
00:22:54,849 --> 00:22:56,282
What about you?

363
00:22:58,353 --> 00:23:01,720
Benny, how old
would you take me to be?

364
00:23:01,790 --> 00:23:04,224
Oh, I'd say
about 20, 21 .

365
00:23:04,292 --> 00:23:05,281
Thanks.

366
00:23:05,360 --> 00:23:08,227
But if he ever
sees my birth certificate,

367
00:23:08,296 --> 00:23:09,228
I'm cooked.

368
00:23:09,297 --> 00:23:10,730
When I joined the navy,

369
00:23:10,799 --> 00:23:12,733
I made a mistake
about my age.

370
00:23:12,801 --> 00:23:14,735
You mean you
weren't 1 7?

371
00:23:14,803 --> 00:23:16,737
I won't be 1 7
for 3 months.

372
00:23:16,805 --> 00:23:18,739
So that's
the way it is.

373
00:23:18,807 --> 00:23:20,240
We're either
too old or young.

374
00:23:20,308 --> 00:23:23,004
Well, kid,
we're in this together.

375
00:23:24,746 --> 00:23:28,079
Every tear

376
00:23:28,149 --> 00:23:32,245
Will be a memory

377
00:23:32,320 --> 00:23:36,222
So wait and pray

378
00:23:36,291 --> 00:23:42,252
Each night for me

379
00:23:42,330 --> 00:23:51,898
Till we meet again

380
00:23:52,007 --> 00:23:53,599
[Ding Ding]

381
00:23:53,675 --> 00:23:55,768
[Ding Ding]

382
00:25:14,289 --> 00:25:16,223
Well, gentlemen...

383
00:25:16,291 --> 00:25:18,088
we have our orders.

384
00:25:24,799 --> 00:25:26,733
[Plays Reveille]

385
00:25:45,720 --> 00:25:46,652
Do it again.

386
00:25:46,721 --> 00:25:47,881
I <i>love</i> it.

387
00:25:52,026 --> 00:25:53,459
Come on, Scott.

388
00:25:53,528 --> 00:25:56,224
30 minutes
to flight quarters.

389
00:25:56,297 --> 00:25:57,730
O.K., O.K.

390
00:25:57,799 --> 00:25:58,925
Come on.

391
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:00,058
Come on.

392
00:26:03,238 --> 00:26:06,173
No wonder they gave you
the Navy Cross.

393
00:26:06,241 --> 00:26:09,836
Waking people up at night,
you have to be a hero.

394
00:26:09,911 --> 00:26:11,902
Your squadron
ahead of ours?

395
00:26:11,980 --> 00:26:13,914
I'm not flying
right now.

396
00:26:13,982 --> 00:26:15,574
Just shower call
and such.

397
00:26:15,650 --> 00:26:18,619
I was on the sick list
after Pearl Harbor.

398
00:26:18,686 --> 00:26:20,620
Still wobbly
on the pins.

399
00:26:20,688 --> 00:26:22,212
Wake Chisholm, will you?

400
00:26:22,290 --> 00:26:23,222
Yeah.

401
00:26:42,210 --> 00:26:44,235
Good morning.

402
00:26:50,852 --> 00:26:53,286
I'll need
five empty fuel containers,

403
00:26:53,354 --> 00:26:54,787
some potassium nitrate,

404
00:26:54,856 --> 00:26:58,155
some calcium nitrate,
manganese sulfate--

405
00:26:58,226 --> 00:27:00,285
Mananganese what, sir?

406
00:27:00,361 --> 00:27:04,593
Manganese sulfate,
and about 30 feet of wire mesh.

407
00:27:04,666 --> 00:27:08,602
And get lots of excelsior
from the engine packings,

408
00:27:08,670 --> 00:27:09,602
and, um...

409
00:27:09,671 --> 00:27:12,003
a big ball of heavy string.

410
00:27:13,341 --> 00:27:14,273
Yeah.

411
00:27:14,342 --> 00:27:15,775
Very good, sir.

412
00:27:15,844 --> 00:27:19,780
May I ask what all these things
are for, sir?

413
00:27:19,848 --> 00:27:21,110
Tomatoes.

414
00:27:21,182 --> 00:27:23,707
Oh, tomatoes.

415
00:28:24,245 --> 00:28:26,179
When you return
from your search,

416
00:28:26,247 --> 00:28:28,977
you will notice the carrier
will be towing a sled.

417
00:28:29,050 --> 00:28:30,984
It's more like a spar

418
00:28:31,052 --> 00:28:33,316
about the size
of a telephone pole.

419
00:28:33,387 --> 00:28:36,322
As each plane comes in,
it will make one pass,

420
00:28:36,390 --> 00:28:39,120
dropping its bomb
well astern of the sled.

421
00:28:39,193 --> 00:28:42,128
Don't hit it. We don't want
the flight deck

422
00:28:42,196 --> 00:28:44,391
showered
with bomb fragments.

423
00:28:46,300 --> 00:28:49,701
Every hour we continue
on our present course

424
00:28:49,770 --> 00:28:52,705
brings nearer the possibility
of contact

425
00:28:52,773 --> 00:28:55,537
with enemy aircraft.

426
00:28:55,609 --> 00:28:58,544
Your orders are these.

427
00:28:58,612 --> 00:29:02,548
When enemy planes
are encountered...

428
00:29:02,616 --> 00:29:05,016
<i>do not</i> engage them.

429
00:29:05,086 --> 00:29:07,646
Return to the carrier
at once.

430
00:29:07,722 --> 00:29:10,156
By '' Do not engage,''
you mean--

431
00:29:10,224 --> 00:29:11,486
I mean

432
00:29:11,559 --> 00:29:13,390
avoid all contact
with them.

433
00:29:13,461 --> 00:29:15,929
But, sir,
that's running away.

434
00:29:19,900 --> 00:29:21,367
Any other questions?

435
00:29:21,435 --> 00:29:23,665
But suppose the enemy
attacks us, sir?

436
00:29:23,738 --> 00:29:25,535
May we interpret
the orders--

437
00:29:25,606 --> 00:29:28,040
You will not
interpret the orders.

438
00:29:28,109 --> 00:29:29,542
You will obey them.

439
00:29:29,610 --> 00:29:31,237
<i>Pilots,</i>
<i>man your planes.</i>

440
00:29:31,312 --> 00:29:33,974
<i>Pilots,</i>
<i>man your planes.</i>

441
00:29:34,048 --> 00:29:35,447
That's all.

442
00:29:38,786 --> 00:29:40,185
Let's go.

443
00:30:04,478 --> 00:30:05,911
Pilot to Radioman.

444
00:30:05,980 --> 00:30:08,744
You got the dope
on the radio frequencies?

445
00:30:08,816 --> 00:30:10,249
Radioman to Pilot.

446
00:30:10,317 --> 00:30:11,284
Yes, sir.

447
00:30:11,352 --> 00:30:14,719
Frequency 69-7 0.
Secondary 61 -50.

448
00:30:14,789 --> 00:30:15,949
All set, sir.

449
00:30:16,023 --> 00:30:18,014
Pilot to Gunner.

450
00:30:18,092 --> 00:30:19,525
Gunner to Pilot.

451
00:30:19,593 --> 00:30:21,026
All set, sir.

452
00:30:21,095 --> 00:30:23,962
Maybe I'll get
my first meatball today.

453
00:30:24,031 --> 00:30:26,966
If you see anyJaps,
blow them a kiss.

454
00:30:27,034 --> 00:30:29,025
But don't shoot--
that's an order.

455
00:30:37,778 --> 00:30:39,245
Pilots...

456
00:30:39,313 --> 00:30:41,781
stand by
to start engines.

457
00:30:43,884 --> 00:30:45,909
Stand clear
propellers.

458
00:30:45,986 --> 00:30:47,954
Start engines.

459
00:30:50,524 --> 00:30:52,583
[Engine Starts]

460
00:32:06,567 --> 00:32:07,932
Oh, boy!

461
00:32:11,005 --> 00:32:14,566
I ought to pop you
on the chin.

462
00:32:14,642 --> 00:32:16,872
That's how Billy Tom
knocked me out.

463
00:32:16,944 --> 00:32:19,310
I was born
with a glass jaw,

464
00:32:19,380 --> 00:32:21,712
but otherwise, in the torso,
I'm unvulnerable.

465
00:32:21,782 --> 00:32:23,545
Come on.
Hit me.

466
00:32:32,226 --> 00:32:33,716
Infinitestimal fortitude.

467
00:32:33,794 --> 00:32:37,230
That's what I calls it.

468
00:32:37,298 --> 00:32:39,493
Rock of Gibraltar.

469
00:32:42,036 --> 00:32:43,594
Hold everything.

470
00:32:43,671 --> 00:32:45,104
What you got
there?

471
00:32:45,172 --> 00:32:46,605
Oh, isn't she lovely?

472
00:32:46,674 --> 00:32:47,606
[Wolf Whistles]

473
00:32:47,675 --> 00:32:49,108
Look at that!

474
00:32:49,176 --> 00:32:50,108
Wow!

475
00:32:50,177 --> 00:32:51,610
A love note.

476
00:32:51,679 --> 00:32:53,112
Come on, read it.

477
00:32:53,180 --> 00:32:54,613
Get out.
Come on.

478
00:32:54,682 --> 00:32:55,808
'' Dearest Hallam,

479
00:32:55,883 --> 00:32:58,750
I couldn't sleep thinking
how lucky the girl was

480
00:32:58,819 --> 00:33:01,652
in your picture
I saw last night

481
00:33:01,722 --> 00:33:03,485
and thinking
how wonderful it would be

482
00:33:03,557 --> 00:33:05,525
if I could have been her

483
00:33:05,593 --> 00:33:07,857
and feel your strong arms
around me...

484
00:33:07,928 --> 00:33:11,921
and your lips
pressed close to mine.''

485
00:33:11,999 --> 00:33:13,796
- Wait a minute!
- Hey!

486
00:33:18,672 --> 00:33:21,607
Hey, get a load of this,
fellas.

487
00:33:21,675 --> 00:33:23,108
'' Dear hunk of man,

488
00:33:23,177 --> 00:33:25,111
I'm a hep chick
who thinks

489
00:33:25,179 --> 00:33:27,773
you're a solid piece
of what it takes.''

490
00:33:27,848 --> 00:33:31,249
Potassium phosphate,

491
00:33:31,318 --> 00:33:32,250
potassium nitrate,

492
00:33:32,319 --> 00:33:33,251
magnesium sulfate,

493
00:33:33,320 --> 00:33:34,753
and calcium nitrate.
O.K.

494
00:33:34,822 --> 00:33:37,882
What are you going
to use these for?

495
00:33:40,728 --> 00:33:41,660
Shh.

496
00:33:41,729 --> 00:33:42,991
Tomatoes.

497
00:33:43,063 --> 00:33:44,223
Tomatoes.

498
00:33:44,298 --> 00:33:46,391
Tomatoes?

499
00:33:46,467 --> 00:33:47,491
Yeah.

500
00:34:31,779 --> 00:34:34,509
I'm glad you dropped in,
Mr. Cunningham.

501
00:34:34,581 --> 00:34:37,209
I wanted to congratulate you
on your citation.

502
00:34:37,284 --> 00:34:39,946
Thank you very much,
Commander.

503
00:34:42,089 --> 00:34:45,957
[Whistling <i>My Bonny</i>
<i>Lies Over The Ocean]</i>

504
00:34:50,531 --> 00:34:51,691
Sir,

505
00:34:51,765 --> 00:34:54,700
the medical officer says
I'm completely O.K. again,

506
00:34:54,768 --> 00:34:56,201
in every respect.

507
00:34:56,270 --> 00:34:57,202
That's great.

508
00:34:57,271 --> 00:34:59,205
You agree with the M.O.?

509
00:34:59,273 --> 00:35:02,299
Yes, sir. I'd like
reassignment to flight duty

510
00:35:02,376 --> 00:35:03,468
as soon as possible.

511
00:35:03,544 --> 00:35:04,977
All right, Cunningham.

512
00:35:05,045 --> 00:35:06,478
As soon as possible.

513
00:35:06,547 --> 00:35:07,980
Thank you, sir.

514
00:35:08,048 --> 00:35:09,174
O.K.

515
00:35:09,249 --> 00:35:12,480
Torpedo Squadron Five
returning from search, sir.

516
00:35:12,553 --> 00:35:13,645
Mmm.

517
00:35:15,055 --> 00:35:16,488
Nice kid,
that Cunningham.

518
00:35:16,557 --> 00:35:17,649
Yes, sir.

519
00:35:43,484 --> 00:35:45,213
The stars at night

520
00:35:45,285 --> 00:35:46,718
Are big and bright

521
00:35:46,787 --> 00:35:47,845
[Fires Four Times]

522
00:35:47,921 --> 00:35:50,515
Deep in the heart
ofTexas

523
00:35:50,591 --> 00:35:52,525
The prairie sky

524
00:35:52,593 --> 00:35:53,924
Is wide and high

525
00:35:53,994 --> 00:35:54,961
[Fires Four Times]

526
00:35:55,028 --> 00:35:57,019
Deep in the heart
ofTexas

527
00:35:57,097 --> 00:35:59,531
What are you shooting at,
Mr. Scott?

528
00:36:03,604 --> 00:36:06,038
Well, nothing.
I'm just testing my guns.

529
00:36:06,106 --> 00:36:07,573
Oh.

530
00:36:12,446 --> 00:36:13,470
All personnel,

531
00:36:13,547 --> 00:36:17,278
clear the afterdeck
